	<td class="alt1">
	<!-- message, attachments, sig -->
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<span class="time"><strong>Re: Explain what is the role of a Monk in groups today.</strong></span>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#606B73" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Tolkienfan wrote:<font color="#7F7FFF"><br />
&gt; Having read many of the monk forums it seems that a monk's usefulness<br />
&gt; to a group has been diminished.  Rogues are sought after more due to<br />
&gt; the fact that they can out damage a monk.  Warriors are sought after<br />
&gt; due to their mitigation advantage and their new abilities to generate<br />
&gt; hate.<br />
&gt;<br />
&gt; After many parses of higher level monks it appears that there is a<br />
&gt; soft cap on monk ac of 1340.  After that point, additional AC has<br />
&gt; little to no return value.  Monks go through life with weight<br />
&gt; restrictions but, higher level monks who actually are able to get<br />
&gt; their hands on excellent gear can easily blow the 1340 AC soft cap<br />
&gt; away.  Then weight seems to no longer be an issue. Big deal if you<br />
&gt; are over weight as a Monk, as long as your AC is over 1340 then you<br />
&gt; are still maxed out on your defense potential.</font><br />
<br />
The AC &quot;soft cap&quot; changes with every expansion.  In GoD, no soft cap has<br />
been reached; every bit of ac makes a difference.<br />
<font color="#7F7FFF"><br />
&gt; The Monk Mitigation Nerf took place before POP was released.  Having<br />
&gt; researched this subject I learned that the nerf was intended to slow<br />
&gt; down the top 5% of Monks but ended up hurting the entire class.  Now,<br />
&gt; some 18+ months after the Monk Mitigation Nerf, monks still have<br />
&gt; problems with POP and above mobs going through them like a meat<br />
&gt; grinder.  Low end monks that do not have decent equipment have this<br />
&gt; problem magnified.</font><br />
<br />
Where exactly are monks being put through the meat grinder?  Monks aren't<br />
warriors, paladins, or shadow knights.  I as a necromancer have &quot;tanked&quot;<br />
named in BoT.  Monks with which I am guilded have off tanked Sol Ro trash<br />
mobs.  So unless you are talking elemental/Sol Ro minis/named, where is it<br />
that monks are incapable of surviving an encounter with a PoP mob?  If you<br />
mean monks are not making effective tanks for xp groups, then I would agree<br />
with you, but I would also add that it isn't their role.<br />
<font color="#7F7FFF"><br />
&gt; One of the motivations for the Nerf seems to have been that Warriors<br />
&gt; were complaining that they were being overlooked by groups for<br />
&gt; tankage duty or at the least had to compete with Monks for tankage<br />
&gt; duty.  Well warriors now have their new hate producing toys that<br />
&gt; Monks do not.</font><br />
<br />
Monks don't get hate producing abilites or weapons because they shouldn't be<br />
getting aggro off of those classes on whom it belongs, namely: Warriors,<br />
Paladins, Shadow Knights, Rangers, and Wizards who can't use concussion.<br />
<br />
<font color="#7F7FFF"><br />
&gt;Since this is the case, why not give Monks back their<br />
&gt; original mitigation abilities? Beastlords who are suppose to be<br />
&gt; hybrids of monks can already out damage monks and bring valuable<br />
&gt; tools to groups.  Rogues can out damage monks, Warriors and Knights<br />
&gt; can generate more hate than monks and also have much more hit points<br />
&gt; and better damage mitigation than monks.  Other than pulling old<br />
&gt; world yard trash what else can monks do that would make high end<br />
&gt; groups want them?</font><br />
<br />
Monks can do damage and they can pull.  Yes, in some places other classes<br />
make better pullers than monks.  The typical example would be LDoN<br />
adventures, where, because of the time limit, splitting mobs with fd is too<br />
time consuming.  The phantom line of disciplines, however, has made monks a<br />
viable puller for adventures where the group can handle an extra mob or two<br />
on occation.  In PoP xp zones (BoT, Sol Ro, Earth, Water) monks make fine<br />
pullers in my experience.  As for being out damaged by rogues, aside from<br />
being able to use SoS to scout, which is of limited use in an xp group, what<br />
are rogues bringing to the group besides damage?<br />
<br />
From your argument, it seems as if you want monks to have some role that<br />
will make them invaluable and a near necessity to every group.  That won't<br />
and shouldn't happen.  When it comes to xp groups, no class is a must have.<br />
<br />
It might seem like a trite answer, but if you personally are severly<br />
dissatisfied with being a monk, then I would reccomend finding a different<br />
class to play that has the abilities you want to use.  I think that many<br />
classes want to feel that they are the absolute best at some important<br />
aspect of the game.  Doing that, however, and trying to balance all the<br />
classes is an impossibility.  As a necromancer, there are some changes that<br />
I think would bring my class more in balance with other classes (foremost a<br />
higher % chance to crit dots), but nothing so egregious that I think I need<br />
to look for a new main.<br />
<br />
--<br />
Sinaiel Soulmerchant<br />
Arch Lich of Misericordia<br />
on Brell Serilis<br />
